      <div xml:id="NA113-kiḷavi">
        <p type="edition">iḵtu iṭaiccurattu āṟṟāṉāya talaivaṉ colliyatu.</p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">This is what he said who was unable to bear it in the middle of the desert.</p>
      </div>
      <div xml:id="NA113">
        <lg type="edition">
<l>            uḻaiyaṇan tuṇṭa viṟaivāṅ kuyarciṉaip</l>
<l>            pullarai yirattip potippuṟap pacuṅkāy</l>
<l>            kalcēr ciṟuneṟi malkat tāam</l>
<l>            peruṅkā ṭiṟantu meytavan taṉavā</l>
<l>            laruñceyaṟ poruṭpiṇi muṉṉi yāmē </l>
<l>            cēṟu maṭantai yeṉṟaliṟ ṟāṉṟa</l>
<l>            ṉeyta luṇkaṇ paital kūrap</l>
<l>            piṉṉiruṅ kūntaliṉ maṟaiyiṉaḷ peritaḻin</l>
<l>            tutiyaṉ maṇṭiya volitalai ñāṭpi</l>
<l>            ṉimmeṉ peruṅkaḷat tiyava rūtu </l>
<l>            māmpalaṅ kuḻali ṉēṅkik</l>
<l>            kalaṅkaña ruṟuvōḷ pulampuko ṇōkkē.</l>
    </lg>
       <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l>They have come to reach [us] indeed, traversing the big wilderness,</l>
<l rend="indent">where the stout-backed(?)<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">iratti poti puṟa(m)</term>: T.V.G. explains <term xml:lang="ta">iratti</term> here to be a thorn-apple tree, with <term xml:lang="ta">poti</term> as a kind of sweet and semi-solid pulp around the seeds.</note> green unripe fruits of the low-trunked</l>
<l rend="indent3">Jujube tree from</l>
<l rend="indent">the high branch with bending twigs(?)<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">iṟai</term> is strange here, but perhaps it can refer to the "joints" of the branch, i.e. the twigs, which are bending/hanging down and can thus be reached by the deer, when they lift their heads. T.V.G. explains the expression <term xml:lang="ta">iṟaivāṅku</term> as meaning "a little bent" here.</note>, eaten, head lifted, by the deer,</l>
<l rend="indent">spread increasingly on the small path joined with stones,</l>
<l>– the looks full of loneliness of her who has agitating grief,</l>
<l rend="indent2">lamenting like the flute [from the stem of] the white waterlily</l>
<l rend="indent3">that is blown by the musician(?)<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">iyavaṉ</term> is given as "drummer" in the TL, but since one usually does not blow a drum and there is a <term xml:lang="ta">kuḻal</term> in the next line we have to assume that it means "musician" in a further sense.</note> on the resounding(?) big field</l>
<l rend="indent3">of the noisy main(?) battle that rushed against<note place="foot">Or: "to which Utiyaṉ rushed".</note> Utiyaṉ,</l>
<l rend="indent2">greatly desolate, hiding herself in her braided dark tresses,</l>
<l rend="indent3">while suffering was abundant in her waterlily kajal eyes,</l>
<l rend="indent3">when [we] said: “we will go, girl”,</l>
<l>we, who have been thinking enticed by wealth difficult to make.</l>
        </lg>
